Title : Amaru (mythology)
Text : [[File:AmaruMitoPeru.jpg|left|thumb|192px|Amaru]]
{{Other uses|Amaru (disambiguation){{!}}Amaru}}
[[File:Amaru kero.jpg|thumb|An amaru depicted on a [[Qiru]].]]
In mythology of [[Andean civilizations]] of South America''',''' the '''amaro''', '''amaru''' ([[Quechuan languages|quechua]]) or '''katari''' ([[Aymara language|aymara]]) is a mythical [[snake|serpent]] or [[dragon]],  most associated with the [[Tiwanaku]] and [[Inca empire]]s.  In [[Inca mythology]], the amaru is a huge double-headed serpent that dwells underground, at the bottom of lakes and rivers.<ref name=Steele2004>{{cite book|last=Steele|first=Paul R.|title=Handbook of Inca Mythology|date=2004|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=1576073548|pages=95–98|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6Wa9RwqdqEkC&pg=PA95#v=onepage&q&f=false|chapter=Encyclopedia of Mythic Narratives, Themes, and Concepts}}</ref>  Illustrated with the heads of a bird and pumas, amarus can be seen emerging from a central element in the center of a stepped mountain or pyramid motif in the [[Gateway of the Sun]] at Tiwanaku, Bolivia. When illustrated on religious vessels, the amaru is often seen with bird-like feet and wings,<ref name="Smith2011Tiwanaku">{{cite journal |author=Smith, S. |year=2011 |title=Generative landscapes: the step mountain motif in Tiwanaku iconography. |journal=Ancient America |volume=12 |pages=1–69 |url=http://www.precolumbia.com/bearc/CAAS/AA12.pdf |format=Automatic PDF download}}</ref> so that it resembles a dragon. The amaru was believed capable of transgressing boundaries to and from the spiritual realm of the subterranean world.<ref name="Smith2011Tiwanaku"/>

